<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-03-08T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-03-08T17:00:00-05:00" n="570" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d570">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/17369</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">El Paso</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-03-08T15:00:00-07:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 8, 1916, 3 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Carranza Consul has called on Carranza for troops. This situation is
                            putting Carranza Government to a critical test. If Villa is permitted to
                            remain in the open as at present, without efficient action by the
                            Carranza forces, it will encourage border opposition to Carranza and
                            tend greatly to undermine the <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi>
                            Government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cobb</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>